---
import BlogPostLayout from '../../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
import { getBlogPost } from '../../lib/blog-posts';
import JaggedFrontier from '../../components/JaggedFrontier';

export const frontmatter = {
  title: 'Jagged Intelligence',
  description:
    'LLMs are superhuman at some tasks and trivially bad at others. The fix is not to make them act human — it is to engineer around the surface.',
  author: 'Adelphi Liong',
  date: '2026-06-21',
  topic: 'tech' as const,
  tags: ['llm', 'ai', 'mental-models'],
  shareMessage: 'LLM capability is a jagged surface, not a ladder. Stop role-playing it human and engineer around it.',
};

const post = getBlogPost('jagged-intelligence')!;
---

<BlogPostLayout post={post}>
  <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
    <em
      >The same model that drafts a working migration script in four seconds will then insist that "strawberry" has two
      r's. It is smart and bad at the same time — superhuman at some things, then tripping over tasks a child would get
      right. That contradiction is not a bug to wait out. It is the most important thing to understand about working with
      these models, and it changes how you should hand them work.</em
    >
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Smart and bad at the same time</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Spend a week with a frontier model and you collect a strange list. It will translate a dense legal paragraph between
    two languages better than most professionals. It will refactor a file, write the tests, and explain the trade-offs.
    Then you ask it to count the letters in a word, or play a clean game of tic-tac-toe, or add a column of large
    numbers, and it falls flat — confidently, with no hint that anything went wrong.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The instinct is to treat this as noise: the model is "having a bad day," or you phrased it wrong, or it will be fixed
    in the next version. That framing keeps you from seeing the actual shape of the thing. The failures are not random
    and they are not temporary glitches around a steadily-rising average. They are <strong>structural</strong>. The model
    is genuinely excellent and genuinely incompetent across a single conversation, and which is which does not follow the
    pattern you expect.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Karpathy's jagged frontier</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Andrej Karpathy</strong> gave this its name: <strong>jagged intelligence</strong>. His observation is that a
    model's capability is a <em>jagged frontier</em> — it pokes far above human ability in some directions while dipping
    below trivial competence in others, all at the same level of "intelligence." There is no single dial labelled smart
    that you can turn up and watch every skill rise together. Progress in one area tells you almost nothing about a
    neighbouring one.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-primary pl-6 py-1 my-6 italic text-muted-foreground">
    The model is not uniformly a bit smarter than last year. It is wildly uneven — and the unevenness is the point, not
    an imperfection on the way to smoothness.
  </blockquote>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Credit where it is due: the frontier framing is Karpathy's, and it is the right starting point. What follows is where
    we take it — because once you accept the shape, the way you <em>use</em> these models has to change.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The wrong picture: the ladder</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Most of us carry a default mental model of intelligence: a <strong>ladder</strong>. A single scalar. Novice at the
    bottom, expert at the top, everyone else ranked somewhere in between. It is how we talk about people — junior, mid,
    senior — and it quietly leaks into how we talk to models.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    This is why so much prompting advice feels like it <em>should</em> work. "You are a senior staff engineer." "Respond
    as Warren Buffett." "Treat it like a smart intern." Each of these is an attempt to place the model on the human
    ladder — to slide it up a rung and collect the competence that comes with the higher position. The intuition is: if I
    can convince it to be more senior, it will be more capable across the board, the way a senior human is.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    But there is no board. The ladder assumes a single axis where moving up lifts everything. The model does not have one
    axis. Telling it to "be a senior engineer" does not raise its arithmetic, its letter-counting, or its game-playing —
    those live in completely different parts of the surface, untouched by the role you assigned. The role prompt can
    change tone and framing; it cannot relocate a capability the model does not have to a rung where it does.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The right picture: a surface</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    The honest model is not a line but a <strong>surface</strong>. Capability varies across at least three things at
    once: the <strong>model</strong> you are using, the <strong>input</strong> you give it, and the <strong>task</strong>
    you are asking for. Hold a model fixed and the competence still rises and falls dramatically as you move across tasks
    — and it does not track human intuition. The things that are hard for us (translation, recall across a huge document,
    generating boilerplate) are often where it spikes. The things that are easy for us (counting, exact arithmetic,
    keeping a simple game state straight) are often where it dips.
  </p>

  <JaggedFrontier client:load />

  <p class="mb-6">
    Look at the two pictures side by side. On the left, the ladder: tidy, ranked, one dimension, the thing our role
    prompts are quietly aiming at. On the right, the truth: spikes that clear the human baseline and dips that fall to
    nearly nothing, sitting right next to each other with no smooth path between them. You cannot summarise that right
    panel with a single number, and you cannot improve it by asking it to stand on a higher rung.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">The implication: engineer around the surface</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Here is the part that matters, and the part that is ours rather than borrowed. If capability is jagged, you cannot
    patch the dips by making the model act more human. Role-play does not move the surface. So stop trying. The job is not
    to coax a person out of the model — it is to <strong>engineer around the surface you actually have</strong>.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">That reframes the whole problem into a division of labour. There are really three things to map:</p>

  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>What you are good at</strong> — judgment, taste, knowing what "done" means, catching the failure the model cannot see.</li>
    <li><strong>What the model is good at</strong> — the spikes: volume, recall, transformation, tireless drafting.</li>
    <li><strong>What the model is bad at</strong> — the dips: the trivial-looking things it will confidently get wrong.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Once those are mapped, you divide the work along the contours. Give the model the spikes. Keep the judgment for
    yourself. Build scaffolding — verification, tools, structure — to cover the dips so a known weakness never becomes a
    silent failure. You are not arguing the surface into a better shape; you are routing work across it.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Two disciplines grow out of exactly this stance, and they are the subjects of the other posts.
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> is the practice: how to
    work the surface in the real world — making the goal a file, looping on it, and pushing your judgment to the edges so
    the model can run autonomously through the middle.
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a>
    is the theory: what the surface actually <em>is</em>, and how every prompt, tool, and bit of context reshapes it. One
    works the surface; the other explains why working it that way succeeds.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-16 mb-6">Blind spots you can only find by watching</h2>

  <p class="mb-6">
    There is a sharper edge to all of this. The model is bad at <em>different</em> things than a human, and it is bad at
    them <strong>unpredictably</strong>. A human junior fails in ways you can anticipate, because their weaknesses cluster
    where yours once did. The model's blind spots do not. They sit in places that feel safe — short inputs, simple
    arithmetic, a small puzzle — precisely where you would never think to check.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    Which means you cannot learn the surface from documentation or from a benchmark score. You learn a given model's
    blind spots the only way available: by <strong>watching it work</strong>, on your tasks, and noticing where it breaks.
    That is also why neither blanket trust nor blanket distrust is rational. Trust everything and the silent dips burn
    you. Distrust everything and you throw away the spikes that make the model worth using. The workable stance is the
    engineered one — trust it where you have mapped a spike, verify it where you have mapped a dip, and keep updating the
    map as you go.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-6">
    If you only take one idea from this: <strong>intelligence here is not a height to climb, it is a shape to map.</strong>
    Stop placing the model on the human ladder. Find its frontier, find yours, and divide the work where they meet. To
    understand <em>why</em> these models behave this way at all, start with
    <a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">how LLMs actually work</a> — the mechanics under the
    chat box.
  </p>

  <div class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground mb-3">Related</p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-muted-foreground">
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/how-llms-work">How LLMs Actually Work</a> — the mechanics under the chat box</li>
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/autonomous-agents">Autonomous Agents</a> — working the surface in practice</li>
      <li><a class="text-primary hover:underline" href="/blog/probability-space-engineering">Probability Space Engineering</a> — the theory of shaping outputs</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
